`crates/steno/src` is the `steno` compiler library: it turns fenced `.steno` theory source into Plover JSON dictionaries, LSP snippet tables, and `@literal`-block keystroke sequences, plus the smart-editor keystroke simulation those artifacts rely on. Everything downstream (the four binaries in `bin/`) consumes only the re-exports in `lib.rs`; nothing outside this crate reaches into a submodule directly, so any renamed re-export is a breaking change felt in `build-dict`, `build-nvim`, `measure`, and `viz-data` simultaneously.

The pipeline is strictly staged and one-directional: `parse/` (source text → `Entry`/`Chunk` AST) → `expand/` (three ordered passes producing `TypedEntry`) → `render/` and `snippet/` (two independent consumers of `TypedEntry`, producing Plover dict entries and LSP snippet bodies respectively) → `json_out.rs` (deterministic serialization for both). `stroke/` and `editor/` are cross-cutting engines rather than pipeline stages: `stroke/` is invoked by `expand/` and `parse/`-adjacent code whenever a stroke needs count-merging or canonical rendering; `editor/`'s `Event`/`interpret`/`movement_events`/`serialize` are the shared keystroke IR that both `render/` (via its `PLAIN`/`SMART` profile split) and `blocks.rs` (for `@literal` structural templates) compile down to. `error.rs` supplies one error type per stage, and every pipeline stage funnels failures into its corresponding error type rather than panicking — this no-panic-on-expected-failure invariant holds crate-wide, down through the binaries in `bin/`.

Two contracts span multiple subtrees. First, `render/`'s and `snippet/`'s terminal/non-terminal classification of a `TypedEntry` (set during `expand/`'s pipeline) must be reasoned about in both consumers independently — getting it wrong in either produces silently-wrong output, not a crash. Second, `editor/`'s `Behaviors` presets (`PLAIN`/`SMART`/`SMART_INDENT`) are consumed by `render/` and effectively define its `SMART`-vs-`PLAIN` output difference (auto-close stripping) without any corresponding code in `render/` itself — a behavior change in `editor/` silently changes dictionary output. `json_out.rs`'s `OrderedMap` insertion-order semantics are relied on by both `render/`'s `build_dict` and `snippet/`'s `build_snippets` for deterministic, diffable output, and its escaping must stay byte-for-byte matched to the TS implementation it mirrors.

A typical cross-cutting change starts in `parse/mod.rs` (new AST/`Chunk` variant), `expand/mod.rs` (new pass or changed intermediate struct), or `editor/mod.rs` (new `Event` variant or `Behaviors` field) — each of those ripples into every downstream stage that pattern-matches its exact shape.